        <p>The efficacy of different cognitive rehabilitative interventions for PwMS varies<sup>80</sup> with some of the most efficacious, evidence based techniques being:</p>

        <ul>
            <li><span>Computer assisted programmes targeting attention and memory<sup>81,82</sup></span></li>
            <li><span>Using memory notebooks for consolidating information<sup>83</sup></span></li>
            <li><span>Using story memory techniques for verbal learning and improving memory<sup>84</sup> </span></li>
        </ul>

        <p>
            Research has highlighted that physical activity affects cognition in some PwMS. Reported benefits of yoga in PwMS populations include reduced fatigue 
            and improved attention<sup>85</sup>. A 2011 study demonstrated a positive correlation between physical activity and cognitive processing speed in 
            ambulatory PwMS<sup>86</sup>. Whilst definite conclusions cannot be drawn from these studies, the positive association between physical activity and 
            cognitive function suggests that physical activity might be an efficacious non-pharmacological treatment for cognitive impairment in MS and as such, should be encouraged.
        </p>
